#compdef tobaru
# =============================================================================
# tobaru — cfal's "Port forwarding CLI utility with allowlists,
#          TLS SNI and ALPN routing, HTTP forwarding, load
#          balancing, IP-to-destination mapping, and iptables
#          support" — a Rust async network proxy daemon for
#          TCP/UDP port forwarding with hot-reload of YAML/JSON
#          config files at runtime via notify filesystem watcher.
#          Distinguishing from socat, iptables, nginx stream
#          modules, HAProxy, and other port forwarders by:
#            - TLS SNI + ALPN ROUTING — single port can host
#              multiple TLS targets routed by SNI hostname
#              and/or ALPN protocol; tobaru parses TLS
#              ClientHello + ALPN extension WITHOUT terminating
#              TLS, forwarding to upstream based on
#              negotiated protocol (HTTP/1.1, HTTP/2, gRPC,
#              custom)
#            - IP ALLOWLISTS via ip_network_table-deps-treebitmap
#              — per-target IPv4/IPv6 CIDR allowlists with
#              O(log N) prefix-tree lookup
#            - LOAD BALANCING with round-robin / weighted
#              round-robin per target
#            - IP-TO-DESTINATION MAPPING — client IP determines
#              which upstream the connection routes to
#            - iptables INTEGRATION via use_iptables — tobaru
#              automatically inserts MATCHING iptables NAT
#              rules for the addresses + targets, enabling
#              transparent proxy mode; --clear-iptables-all
#              cleans up on shutdown
#            - HTTP FORWARDING with Host-header-based routing
#              (in addition to TCP-level routing)
#            - rustls + aws-lc-rs FOR PURE-RUST TLS — no
#              OpenSSL dependency; aws-lc-rs (Amazon's BoringSSL
#              fork) provides the crypto primitives; rustls
#              handles TLS protocol; both pure-Rust builds
#            - HOT RELOAD via notify — config file changes
#              detected via filesystem watch; running servers
#              restart with new config without dropping existing
#              connections
#            - URL-EMBEDDED CONFIGS — pass forwarding rules
#              directly on CLI as URLs:
#                tobaru tcp://127.0.0.1:1000?target=127.0.0.1:2000
#                tobaru udp://0.0.0.0:5060?target=10.0.0.5:5060
#            - TOKIO MULTI-THREADED RUNTIME — --threads N
#              configures worker thread count; defaults to
#              std::thread::available_parallelism()
#            - DRY-RUN MODE via --dry-run — validates config
#              files without starting servers (useful for CI)
#          Used by: home-lab + small-shop network administrators
#          replacing socat scripts, multi-tenant TLS routing
#          deployments needing SNI-based routing without nginx,
#          and as a reference implementation of notify + rustls
#          + tokio + serde_yaml + iptables-NAT composition in
#          Rust.
#
# Author:  cfal (GitHub username) — Rust network-programming
#          enthusiast.  tobaru released ~2021; active development
#          through 2026; current version 0.9.5.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/cfal/tobaru
#          https://github.com/cfal/tobaru/blob/master/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/cfal/tobaru/blob/master/Cargo.toml
# CLI:     src/main.rs — manual `std::env::args()` flag parsing
#          (no clap dependency; lightweight argument handling).
#          Headline library: **notify** (notify is the new
#          variant being documented here, opening Axis 17 —
#          File Watching).
# Library: notify (https://github.com/notify-rs/notify —
#          "Cross-platform filesystem notification library for
#           Rust" — François Mockers + notify-rs team.
#           Distinct from all previously-documented Rust
#           libraries by being:
#              1. CROSS-PLATFORM FILESYSTEM EVENTS — single API
#                 abstracting over four kernel-level event
#                 sources:
#                   * Linux:   inotify (kernel 2.6.13+)
#                   * macOS:   FSEvents (kernel-level) + kqueue
#                   * Windows: ReadDirectoryChangesW (Win32 API)
#                   * BSDs:    kqueue
#                 RecommendedWatcher chooses the best available
#                 backend at compile time per target platform.
#              2. EVENT KIND TAXONOMY — Event::kind enum covers:
#                   EventKind::Create(CreateKind::*)
#                   EventKind::Modify(ModifyKind::*)
#                       Modify(Data(DataChange::*))
#                       Modify(Metadata(MetadataKind::*))
#                       Modify(Name(RenameMode::*))
#                   EventKind::Remove(RemoveKind::*)
#                   EventKind::Access(AccessKind::*)
#                   EventKind::Other
#                 — granular event classification for filtering.
#              3. CHANNEL-BASED API — watchers are constructed
#                 with a closure / channel that receives
#                 notify::Result<Event> for each filesystem
#                 change:
#                   let mut watcher = notify::recommended_watcher(
#                     move |res: notify::Result<Event>| match res {
#                       Ok(event) => tx.send(event).unwrap(),
#                       Err(e) => eprintln!("watch err: {:?}", e),
#                     }
#                   ).unwrap();
#                   watcher.watch(Path::new("config.yaml"),
#                                 RecursiveMode::NonRecursive)?;
#              4. RECURSIVE / NON-RECURSIVE WATCHING — paths can
#                 be watched RECURSIVELY (all descendants) or
#                 NON-RECURSIVELY (path only).  Recursive watch
#                 of a directory captures all descendants without
#                 manually iterating contents.
#              5. DEBOUNCED VARIANT — notify-debouncer-mini and
#                 notify-debouncer-full provide event coalescing
#                 (combine multiple Modify events into one) for
#                 reducing event-storm overhead from editors
#                 that write multiple times.
#              6. POLL-BASED FALLBACK — PollWatcher (vs
#                 RecommendedWatcher) uses periodic stat() polls
#                 for platforms without inotify/FSEvents/etc.,
#                 or for filesystems where kernel events are
#                 unreliable (NFS, virtual FS).
#              7. ATTRIBUTE FILTERING — Config-level filters can
#                 ignore certain event kinds (e.g. ignore Access
#                 events to reduce noise from `stat` calls).
#              8. NO-STD COMPATIBLE for core types via notify-
#                 types crate.
#              9. WIDELY ADOPTED — used by cargo-watch, watchexec,
#                 dprint, mprocs, tobaru (THIS), zellij, alacritty
#                 config reload, helix editor file-watch, etc.
#             10. NOTIFY-RS GROUP MAINTAINER — multi-maintainer
#                 group (François Mockers, daboross, 0xpr03,
#                 dfaust, etc.) under notify-rs GitHub org.
# License: MIT OR Apache-2.0 (notify); MIT (tobaru)
# Status:  notify — 3,379+ stars on notify-rs/notify, ~90M
#          crates.io downloads (TOP-100 Rust crate by downloads);
#          foundational filesystem-event library used by:
#            * cargo-watch (Rust dev hot-reload)
#            * watchexec (universal file-watcher)
#            * dprint (code formatter daemon)
#            * mprocs (multi-process tmux alt)
#            * helix (modal text editor)
#            * zellij (terminal multiplexer)
#            * alacritty (config reload)
#            * starship (cross-shell prompt cache)
#            * tobaru (THIS — port forwarder hot reload)
#            * 2000+ Rust applications
#          tobaru — 284+ stars on cfal/tobaru, used in home-lab
#          + small-shop multi-tenant TLS deployments.
